This folder contains the results comparing the MIP model and the proposed LBBDA model.

Those files whose titles are simply instance names are modified data from Otto 2013. (Systematic data generation and test design for solution algorithms on the example of salbpgen for assembly line balancing. European Journal of Operational Research, 228 (1), 33–45.) The original data are for simple assembly line balancing problem with one product variant, one worker option per task, and no zone-incompatible tasks. 

We add those features in the dataset. Column "Zone Incompatible Tasks" shows the zone-incompatible tasks per task, and multiple tasks are splitted by comma in one cell. Column "Mod" represents the product type for each task. "Resource Option 1" and "Resource Option 2" are the worker options per task. If some tasks don't have the second option, then the cells are blank. We consider two types of workers: "F" denotes foremen, whose cost rates are $90/hr, and "U" denotes unskilled workers, whose cost rates are $60/hr. The cells are formatted in this way: "F_a,U_b: d" means this worker option requires a foremen and b unskilled workers to collaborate, and duration is d min.
